WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:07.000
Good afternoon. I'm Dr. Liu Wei, and this is Ethics in Artificial Intelligence, CS490.

00:00:07.500 --> 00:00:14.000
AI ethics is not soft philosophy — it's an engineering discipline with real-world consequences.

00:00:14.500 --> 00:00:21.000
Every design decision encodes values. The question is whether those values are made explicit.

00:00:21.500 --> 00:00:28.000
Let's start with bias. Machine learning models learn patterns from historical data.

00:00:28.500 --> 00:00:35.000
If that data reflects historical discrimination, the model will reproduce and amplify it.

00:00:35.500 --> 00:00:42.000
Amazon's hiring algorithm, trained on past resumes, systematically downgraded women's applications.

00:00:42.500 --> 00:00:49.000
COMPAS, used to predict recidivism in US courts, showed racial bias in its risk scores.

00:00:49.500 --> 00:00:56.000
These are not edge cases — they are predictable outcomes of training on biased human data.

00:00:56.500 --> 00:01:03.000
Fairness is not a single metric — there are over 20 mathematical definitions, many incompatible.

00:01:03.500 --> 00:01:10.000
Demographic parity requires equal positive prediction rates across groups. Simple but often misleading.

00:01:10.500 --> 00:01:17.000
Equalized odds requires equal true positive and false positive rates — a stronger guarantee.

00:01:17.500 --> 00:01:24.000
Calibration requires that predicted probabilities match actual outcomes across groups.

00:01:24.500 --> 00:01:31.000
It has been proven mathematically that you cannot satisfy all three definitions simultaneously.

00:01:31.500 --> 00:01:38.000
Choosing which fairness criterion to optimize is a value judgment, not a technical decision.

00:01:38.500 --> 00:01:45.000
Transparency and explainability are often confused. Transparency means open access to the model.

00:01:45.500 --> 00:01:52.000
Explainability means the ability to understand why a specific decision was made.

00:01:52.500 --> 00:01:59.000
GDPR's right to explanation creates legal requirements for explainability in automated decisions.

00:01:59.500 --> 00:02:06.000
LIME and SHAP are post-hoc methods that approximate local explanations for black-box models.

00:02:06.500 --> 00:02:13.000
But these approximations can be manipulated — an adversary can game them to produce misleading explanations.

00:02:13.500 --> 00:02:20.000
Privacy is another critical dimension. Models can memorize training data and leak it.

00:02:20.500 --> 00:02:27.000
Membership inference attacks can determine whether a specific person was in the training set.

00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:34.000
Differential privacy adds calibrated noise to training to provide formal privacy guarantees.

00:02:34.500 --> 00:02:41.000
The privacy-utility tradeoff is real — more privacy typically means worse model performance.

00:02:41.500 --> 00:02:48.000
Autonomy and human oversight are increasingly important as AI systems make high-stakes decisions.

00:02:48.500 --> 00:02:55.000
The EU AI Act classifies AI systems by risk level and mandates human oversight for high-risk uses.

00:02:55.500 --> 00:03:02.000
For your essay this week: pick one real-world AI system and analyze it through two fairness lenses.

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:08.000
Argue which lens is most appropriate given the context, and justify your choice.
